Etymology 1[edit]

From sub- +‎ cadō (“fall”).

Alternative forms[edit]

  • subcidō

Pronunciation[edit]

  • (Classical) IPA(key): /ˈsuk.ki.doː/, [ˈsʊk.kɪ.d̪oː]
  • (Ecclesiastical) IPA(key): /ˈsut.t͡ʃi.do/, [ˈsut.t͡ʃi.d̪ɔ]

Verb[edit]

succidō (present infinitive succidere, perfect active succidī); third conjugation, no passive, no supine stem

  1. I fall under something, collapse.
  2. I sink under myself, sink down, sink.

Etymology 2[edit]

From sub- +‎ caedō (“cut; strike”).

Pronunciation[edit]

  • (Classical) IPA(key): /sukˈkiː.doː/, [sʊkˈkiː.d̪oː]
  • (Ecclesiastical) IPA(key): /sutˈt͡ʃi.do/, [sutˈt͡ʃiː.d̪ɔ]

Verb[edit]

succīdō (present infinitive succīdere, perfect active succīdī, supine succīsum); third conjugation

  1. I cut off, through, or away from below, cut or mow down, fell.
